Diamond Prices EDA & ML

Diamond, the most precious gem in the world

What makes a diamond more expensive than another?

Today we're gonna explore the diamond prices dataset to learn more about the factors that influence a diamond price

The clarity of a diamond range from Flawless to I3.

In this dataset, it only goes from IF (internally flawless, to I1)

here we have 8 different values, we are going to replace them with numeral ranging from 1 to 8 (keeping 0 for a flawless diamond)

In [101]:
clarity_map = {'IF': 1, 'VVS1':2, 'VVS2': 3, 'VS1': 4, 'VS2': 5, 'SI1': 6, 'SI2': 7, 'I1': 8}

finally, depth and table are a percentage of the maximum diameter.

An excellent depth is around 60% of the diameter, and for table it between 53 and 60% of the diameter

3. Machine Learning Models Comparison

For this dataset, we are going to compare three machine learning models:

  • Linear Regression
  • Decision Tree
  • XGBoost

4. Target Transform

In this part we are going to try four transform on the target data. When the target distribution is skewed, normalizing the distribution often improve the predictions. However, we must be careful of doing the inverse transform before measuring the error

In [130]:
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.compose import TransformedTargetRegressor
from sklearn.preprocessing import PowerTransformer, QuantileTransformer

boost = GradientBoostingRegressor()

log_transformer = TransformedTargetRegressor(boost, func=np.log, inverse_func=np.exp)
root_transformer = TransformedTargetRegressor(boost, func=np.sqrt, inverse_func=np.square)
power_model = TransformedTargetRegressor(boost, transformer=PowerTransformer(method='box-cox'))
quantile_model = TransformedTargetRegressor(boost, transformer=QuantileTransformer())

Log Transform

In [131]:
log_transformer.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_log = log_transformer.predict(X_test)

mae_log = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_log)
mape_log = mape(y_test, y_pred_log)
r2_log = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_log)

print(f'the mean absolute error for log transformer Gradient Boosting regressor is {round(mae_log, 2)}')
print(f'the mean absolute percent error for log transformed Gradient Boosting regressor is {round(100 * mape_log, 1)}')
print(f'the r2 score for log transformed Gradient Boosting regressor is {round(r2_log, 3)}')

the mean absolute error for log transformer Gradient Boosting regressor is 346.88
the mean absolute percent error for log transformed Gradient Boosting regressor is 9.1
the r2 score for log transformed Gradient Boosting regressor is 0.973

square root transform

5. Data Scaling and Target Transform

The last step is trying to scale the data. We are going to test four combination:

  • StandardScaler and LogTransform
  • RobustScaler and LogTransform
  • StandardScaler and PowerTransform
  • RobustScaler and PowerTransform
In [135]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, RobustScaler

sscaler = StandardScaler()
rscaler = RobustScaler()

StandardScaler and LogTransform

In [136]:

X_test_scaled = sscaler.transform(X_test)

With this dataset, scaling the feature had no effect on the predictions

Summary

  • XGB boost had the best score but it took a lot of time to train
  • Decision Tree and Gradient Boosting had good scores
  • Linear Regression doesn't work well for this problem because it cannot take into consideration the exponential increase of the prices
  • Transforming the target improve the score further because of the data distribution
  • However, scaling the data has no effect, probably because the variables have similar ranges
